entry.summary:
Randomness is weird. Apart from the fact that true randomness on computers can only be achieved with either really complex devices or fish tanks, it just doesn't look appealing, either.
Consider this piece of code:
<canvas id="c" width="640" height="360" />

<script>
const canvas = document.querySelector('#c')

const paintGreyPixel = (canvas, x, y, grayScale) => {
  const context = canvas.getContext('2d')
  context.fillStyle = `rgba(0, 0, 0, ${grayScale})`
  context.fillRect(x, y, 1, 1)
}

for (let x = 0; x < 640; x++) {
  for (let y = 0; y < 360; y++) {
    paintGreyPixel(canvas, x, y, Math.random())
  }
}
</script>

What it does, is to paint every single pixel in a random grey scale. Math.random() combined with rgba and a black color results in a random shade of grey. And that's the resu…
